<DOCNO> AP900318-0001 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the caribbean moon casts a silvery 
light that is kind to the shabby streets and crooked docks of this 
steamy port town on the miskito coast 
the doctors who set bluefields broken bones and deliver its 
babies gather on a porch catching the breeze catching their 
breath waiting for dinner 
they are the cuban medical brigade 15 idealistic envoys of a 
revolution becoming isolated and stale because of changes sweeping 
the rest of the communist world 
suddenly they dont know where they stand 
change has hit nicaragua ousting president daniel ortegas 
leftist sandinistas one of cubas only remaining allies violeta 
barrios de chamorros new government will be conservative and 
proamerican 
will it ask them to stay will cuban president fidel castro let 
them remain to taste postrevolutionary democracy 
the story of the doctors and their compatriots in a 300strong 
construction brigade here is a story of a community in need 
hardwon acceptance and the vagaries of politics 
it began a decade ago when bluefields was torn by anticuban 
riots today many bluefilenos dread the cubans departure 
it would strip nicaraguas isolated south atlantic coast of its 
only surgeons anesthesiologists obstetricians and orthopedist 
it would shatter the vision of a thousand sturdy new homes 
replacing shacks flattened by hurricane joan in 1988 
it would be chaos said dr donald weil the nicaraguan 
director of the sandino regional hospital where more than half the 
staff is cuban 
a few blocks away the cuban doctors gather around their 
communal dinner table talking about work about home about what 
lies ahead 
well be here as long as they want us says dr ernesto diaz 
trujillo a 40yearold intensive care specialist who is 11 months 
into his twoyear tour 
bluefields got a taste of life without the cubans when they 
stayed home in the tense days after the feb 25 election 
they didnt want to come out on the street because they didnt 
know what would be happening said johnny hodgson a local 
sandinista official 
things fell apart at the 118bed hospital which has only 12 
nicaraguan doctors some patients had to be sent to managua 190 
miles west and reachable only by plane or boat most just had to 
wait 
we couldnt handle it dr weil said 
after two days community leaders went to the cubans and 
persuaded them to return to work reassuring them they were not 
only safe but desperately needed 
the experience converted all but the most fervent 
anticommunists in bluefields weil said people changed colors 
like chameleons 
back at the cuban residence the table falls silent as the 
brigades orthopedic surgeon shouts into the telephone reassuring 
his mother back home in cuba 
no problems he yells jamming the receiver into one ear and 
his finger into the other so he can hear absolutely no 
problems 
their voices crossed only 800 miles but it might as well have 
been 800000 
nicaraguas atlantic coast an enclave of mestizos miskito 
indians the descendants of british pirates and of african slaves 
is a universe away from both havana and managua 
anticommunism runs deep a legacy of the regions ties to the 
yankees who mined its gold cut its lumber fished its waters and 
to the missionary fervor of the moravians and the capuchin priests 
who educated its children 
i remember when i was studying in secondary school we had to 
pray after every class hodgson recalled with a laugh and if 
you didnt mention cuba and communism in your prayers it was as if 
you were not praying 
acceptance was a long time in coming for the cubans who began 
arriving in nicaragua soon after the 1979 revolution 
the people of the coast resented the cuban teachers and their 
highly political curriculum 
in september 1980 anticuban riots erupted when the government 
announced plans to send in more teachers thousands of people 
mostly blacks took to the streets 
the government sent in the army to put down the riots arrested 
hundreds of people and accused bluefields of trying to launch a 
separatist movement 
the teachers were eventually withdrawn the doctors stayed 
nearly irreplaceable because of the shortage of physicians in 
nicaragua 
but it took the fury of a hurricane joan on oct 21 1988 to 
bridge the gulf between bluefields and castros envoys 
it was cuba that arrived first with aid and was most generous 
when bluefilenos gathered the boards of 5000 homes scattered like 
matchsticks by 135 mph winds there were cubans by their side 
the construction brigade has put up more than 100 of a planned 
1000 sturdy prefabricated homes the first residents began moving 
late last year into what is now the best neighborhood in town 
this is the first time with the construction of these houses 
that the people of bluefields really live with the cubans you 
know walk with them and pass the whole day with them hodgson 
said 
the construction brigade lives in a cubanbuilt complex that 
will become a university after they leave there are touches of 
home such as cuban cigars cigarettes and coffee 
all of them has a girlfriend or boyfriend they are 
courting said marvin taylor a local politician 
at the former british diplomatic mission where the doctors live 
dinner is over the doctors head back to the porch to the rocking 
chairs under the sign to the lazy moonlight 
trujillo lingers for a moment making a point about people and 
politics about isolation and coexistence 
if i drink red wine and you drink white he says holding a 
glass high there is no reason we cant toast 
</TEXT>
