<DOCNO> AP900318-0002 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
mikhail s gorbachev has once again shaken up the 
soviet political system this time to give himself even more power 
as the countrys first westernstyle president 
but as lithuania leads other small republics toward independence 
and russia itself contemplates electing a chief executive the 
question down the road for gorbachev is president of what 
the congress of peoples deputies the soviet parliament 
grumbled and complained more than usual but thursday acknowledged 
gorbachev as the political master from poland to the bering strait 
and iran to the arctic circle the area includes more than 100 
nationalities and almost 300 million people 
gorbachevs moves early this year leading to his election 
appeared to complete a revolution of the political structure that 
even he until recently did not expect 
in december he fought andrei d sakharov to prevent the 
parliament from eliminating the communist partys guarantee of 
power but two months later he led the fight to end it 
his close politburo adviser alexander n yakovlev told an 
official newspaper that gorbachev opposed a presidential form of 
government and only recently came to believe it was needed to hold 
his country together 
gorbachev told parliament he intends to be president of all the 
people including 37 million lithuanians whose leaders hastily 
declared independence before gorbachev could gain his new powers 
our country is living through difficult times but if we act 
energetically and as a team we certainly will be able to overcome 
the difficulties he said the russian people and all the 
peoples united with it in a great multinational state will succeed 
in reviving their common homeland and will surely achieve that on 
the road of perestroika and socialist renewal 
but his dealings with the wayward republics give little grounds 
for such optimism 
when it declared independence lithuania changed its soviet name 
and emblem and activists report that onethird of its 15000 
potential draftees refused to show up this year for service in the 
soviet army it announced plans to start setting up border 
checkpoints 
on friday gorbachev gave lithuania until monday to answer a 
parliament proclamation that the declaration of independence was 
invalid 
even as he assumed new powers that do not exclude direct 
presidential rule of an area he was faced with the lithuanian 
contagion spreading 
the soviet union will have its president and estonia will 
move toward independence said endel lippmaa a leading deputy 
from the lithuanias fellow baltic republic of 16 million people 
an unofficial estonian congress demanded that the kremlin name 
the time that it would pull its soldiers out estonian government 
officials said they agreed 
latvia the third baltic republic also is pushing for 
independence and the caucasus republic georgia has demanded 
negotiations about restoring independence moldavians are looking 
more closely across the border to their ethnic brothers in romania 
after the revolution there armenia and azerbaijan locked in a 
bloody territorial dispute share a mutual antipathy for gorbachev 
all those republics make up only about 10 percent of the 
countrys population they were collected by the czarist empire 
which broke up after the bolshevik revolution and then gradually 
gathered again by the soviet union the baltics were independent 
countries between the world wars and were the last to join the 
soviet union they were absorbed by josef stalin in 1940 
central asia home to about one in five soviets increasingly 
has been wracked by ethnic violence but so far there has been 
little talk of secession 
but the longslumbering slavic heartland of russia the ukraine 
and byelorussia is showing signs of waking up 
the three republics which contain more than twothirds of the 
countrys people held local elections march 4 runoffs were 
required in most districts but progressives appeared to do well 
perhaps presaging drives for autonomy similar to those gripping the 
smaller republics 
but the rukh movement has gained a foothold in the ukraine with 
its demands for more autonomy and there are appeals for outright 
independence for the secondmost populous republic 
in russia nationalists say that it is the russians themselves 
who have suffered the most from soviet rule unlike other 
republics russia does not have its own capital its own hymn or 
its own communist party structure nationalists are pressing people 
to think of themselves as russians rather than soviets 
the russian federation by far the largest republic already has 
decided to elect its own president one of the announced candidates 
for the job is gorbachevs populist nemesis boris n yeltsin 
yeltsin has nationwide popularity and nationwide ambition he 
said in italy earlier this month that he would like to be soviet 
president if there were a popular vote 
while gorbachev has paid a price in popularity for his 
leadership over the past five years yeltsin has sniped at him for 
not moving faster and his popularity has twice translated into 
impressive electoral victories 
in march 1989 he won almost 90 percent of the vote in sweeping a 
parliament seat from moscow two weeks ago he outpolled more than 
70 percent of the vote in his ural mountain hometown of sverdlovsk 
in a race for a seat in the russian federation congress it is that 
body that will choose the russian president 
if gorbachev cannot hang on to the nonslavic republics there 
will be less and less difference between the territory of the 
russian federation and the territory of the soviet union the two 
chief executives almost certainly would find their interests and 
powers in conflict 
even without the 14 other republics russia would be a huge 
country but not necessarily big enough for two masters 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
mark j porubcansky has reported on the gorbachev revolution 
from moscow since february 1987 
</TEXT>
