<TEXT>
a battle over an experimental hog farm 
that pitted billionaire against billionaire will be decided by 
voters who will choose whether to require the farm to spend 10 
million on a waste treatment plant 
in effect weld county voters must judge tuesday whether the 
bass brothers of fort worth texas have set up an operation using 
unproven methods that could pollute the water supply or whether 
such criticism is a smokescreen orchestrated by a rival tycoon who 
has other reasons for wanting the farm closed 
its very debilitating to be attacked for the very thing you 
think is very special said bill haw president of national hog 
farms 
what haw thinks is special is the hog farm built by his company 
15 miles east of here along the south platte river financial 
backers include four men on the forbes magazine list of richest 
americans texas brothers robert sid lee and edward bass in its 
october issue the magazine estimated that robert was worth 144 
billion sid and lee 125 billion each and edward 1 billion 
but philip anschutz owner of the southern pacific 
transportation co and the subsidiary denver amp rio grande railroad 
doesnt think the hog farm is so special especially since his 
32000acre eagless nest ranch is downstream from it forbes put 
anschutzs worth at 125 billion also chiefly from oil 
the 25750acre farm which began operating last year plans to 
raise 300000 pigs a year in a sterile environment that avoids use 
of antibiotics or other commonly used drugs 
to get rid of the hog waste the farm treats it and uses it to 
fertilize grassland used by grazing cattle haw calls it the most 
environmentally sound livestock operation in the world 
haw said anschutz is just using the environmental issue as a 
ruse to try to acquire the land that national farms now owns haw 
said the farm thwarted anschutzs hopes of expanding his ranch 
where he raises cattle and shoots wild game 
i cant imagine what mr anschutz expects to accomplish other 
than vengeance haw said were certainly not going to leave 
initially anschutz and haw took the issue to court but now it 
is the voters who get to pass judgment the farms owners havent 
said what they will do if the ordinance requiring the treatment 
plant is approved 
both sides have hired denver public relations firms to press 
their arguments and anschutz founded and helped finance a 
citizens group called protect our water 
a vote for the proposed ordinance said gretchen cutts a 
spokeswoman for the group would send the right message to the 
right corporations and the right message to the wrong corporations 
that this is a community that cares about environmental concerns 
but it isnt just the anschutzfunded group that has raised 
environmental questions 
at a hearing last week joann silverstein a university of 
colorado civil engineering professor said the farms waste 
disposal process already may be increasing nitrate levels in ground 
water and in the south platte river and would undoubtedly do so 
further if the farm isnt forced to change its methods 
nitrates are dangerous to pregnant women and have been linked to 
blue baby syndrome a potentially fatal disease in newborns 
caused by lack of oxygen in the blood she said 
at the same hearing however weld county health director randy 
gordon called the fluctuations in nitrate levels normal and said 
there is no proof they are caused by the hog farm 
dan luecke of the environmental defense fund in boulder agrees 
that opponents have a legitimate concern about nitrates from hog 
waste seeping into water 
on a conceptual level you could say spraying the waste water 
on farmland makes sense but i have seen no data on the quality of 
the water going on the land he said 
while both sides expect to win each also concedes that weld 
countys 125000 residents are probably confused about which way to 
vote 
according to county clerk mary ann feuerstein protect our water 
spent 38500 in campaigning through march 4 national hog farms 
has reported spending 5600 up to that date but haw estimates his 
company will spend at least 70000 before the campaigning is 
finished 
nonetheless beverly cruz bartender at the scotch pub in 
greeley said she hasnt heard any of her customers talk about the 
hog farm or the waste 
usually if its something theyre concerned about they will be 
talking about it she said 
</TEXT>
