<DOCNO> AP900318-0007 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
republicans who warned last fall that l 
douglas wilder was a liberal hiding behind conservative rhetoric 
praised the nations first black elected governor for his cautious 
approach in his first legislative session 
wilder opened the general assembly session in january with a 
lecture on fiscal discipline demanding that the legislature come 
up with a 200 million reserve fund for 199192 he ended the 
session by orchestrating a power play to repeal the sales tax on 
nonprescription drugs a cause he has long championed 
but for most of the session wilder took a handsoff approach 
allowing the legislators to do their job his style contrasted 
sharply with that of his predecessor gerald l baliles who 
routinely had aides buttonholing legislators to lobby for his bills 
wilder said at a news conference on the last day of the session 
march 10 that he thought the lawmakers appreciated his approach 
we know how to communicate and weve been doing it a long 
time said wilder who served 16 years in the virginia senate and 
four years as lieutenant governor 
wilders style served him well he got his reserve fund and the 
nonprescription drug tax repeal only four of the 119 bills 
proposed by his administration failed to pass and legislators from 
both political parties went home happy 
governor wilder in his budget restraint showed more of a 
republican philosophy than we could have hoped for said house 
minority leader raymond r guest jr baliles spent everything he 
could wilder is trying to get us back on track 
early in the session wilder endeared himself to republican 
leaders by calling him into his office to brief them on his 
legislative agenda we had more time with the governor today than 
we did the previous four years guest said at the time 
larry sabato a political analyst at the university of virginia 
said the approach was vintage wilder hes inclined to win groups 
that would not otherwise be allied to him 
sabato said the session was a good one for wilder whose 
historic election last november is viewed by many as the first step 
to national office 
his agenda is in two parts sabato said theres the 
virginia part and theres the national part the bottom line is he 
did well for both he projected the image of being a fiscal 
conservative and a taxcutter virginians are pleased and its a 
message he can sell to the national democratic party 
with the exception of the money initiatives wilder did not have 
much of a legislative agenda sabato said that will surprise many 
national observers 
part of it is the race thing he said its the belief 
that black governor equals activist governor thats not 
necessarily so 
most of the 119 administrationproposed bills were not 
controversial just two were rejected outright companion bills 
that would require state employees to pay part of their insurance 
costs the other two one addressing rules governing notaries the 
other on unemployment compensation procedures were tabled or 
withdrawn 
mark rozell a political analyst at mary washington college in 
fredericksburg va was more critical than sabato 
i dont think hes really had a coherent program per se that 
he has articulated rozell said part of that is derived from 
the budgetary crisis which understandably places serious 
constraints on his ability to be a more activist governor 
nonetheless there have been some issues on which wilder could 
have taken a much more assertive leadership role to that extent 
his first session has not been very successful 
rozell criticized wilder for failing to take a clear position on 
such issues as public smoking restrictions and admission of women 
to allmale virginia military institute 
the legislature passed a bill imposing modest statewide 
restrictions on smoking once unthinkable in tobaccoproducing 
virginia wilder has said hes for reasonable smoking restrictions 
but hasnt said whether he will sign the bill another bill 
proposed by a legislator to prohibit sex discrimination in public 
college admissions policies was killed 
rozell said wilders latesession tax repeal victory 
demonstrates how effective a leader he can be should he decide to 
be more assertive wilder argued that the tax on nonprescription 
drugs while not a large cost to the average household was unfair 
in that it fell disproportionately on the elderly and poor 
sabato and most legislators liked the way wilder distanced 
himself from the legislature 
the governor doesnt have to get involved in every little 
squabble sabato said he picked and chose his fights very 
carefully 
governor wilders big goal was to get the budget in shape 
said delegate leslie l byrne a democrat he trusts the 
legislative process and he gave us a free hand to meet the goals 
he wasnt intrusive 
delegate george allen a republican said he appreciated 
wilders silence on many controversial issues 
the legislature was able to work its will allen said 
they werent having their arms twisted into doing things they 
didnt want to do 
</TEXT>
