<TEXT>
from its beginnings as a case of many 
issues the trial of exxon valdez captain joseph hazelwood has come 
down to just two key questions was hazelwood drunk and was he 
reckless to leave the bridge just before his tanker grounded 
beyond the specifics that jurors will consider when they receive 
the case this week is the implicit question of whether the nations 
largest oil spill was an accident or a crime 
this was a maritime accident captain hazelwood was not 
responsible for that accident defense attorney dick madson told 
jurors in opening statements he is expected to make a similar 
point when final arguments are presented tuesday 
the ultimate responsibility for the tanker is with the 
captain said assistant district attorney brent cole in his 
opening statement the most dangerous part of the journey was 
after hazelwood absented himself from the bridge 
although many civil suits were filed after the grounding of the 
exxon valdez a year ago next saturday hazelwood was the only 
member of the ships crew charged criminally 
hazelwood 43 of huntington ny is accused of one felony 
criminal mischief and three misdemeanors reckless endangerment 
operating a vessel while intoxicated and negligent discharge of 
oil if convicted he could face 7 years in prison and 61000 in 
fines 
the tanker rammed a charted reef in prince william sound 
spewing nearly 11 million gallons of alaska north slope crude oil 
devastating fisheries and wildlife and fouling the rocky shoreline 
for hundreds of miles 
cole promised at the outset to prove hazelwood was drunk and 
away from his appropriate post on the bridge during the most 
treacherous part of the tankers voyage in prince william sound 
but his claim that the sound was treacherous was disputed by 
tanker captains who testified for the defense one called it a 
mill pond another said it was like navigating the pacific 
ocean it was so wide open even the prosecutions last 
witness a texaco tanker captain said the sound was not a 
particularly difficult area to navigate and was not crowded with 
the tanker traffic that often blocks other ports 
as testimony piled up over six weeks it became clear that 
headlinemaking reports of a drunken skipper were based on 
circumstantial evidence hazelwood was seen at a bar in the port 
city of valdez the day his ship sailed 
witnesses reported that he drank vodka but how much he drank 
and at what hour remained in dispute three witnesses said they 
smelled alcohol on the skippers breath that night 
but not a single witness described hazelwood as appearing drunk 
no one saw him stagger no one heard him slur his words crew 
members said he negotiated a precarious gangway without missing a 
step they called him cool calm and in command before and after 
the grounding 
the question of inebriation was muddled because authorities 
failed to do a timely blood test hazelwood wasnt tested until 10 
hours after the disaster making the results a dubious gauge of his 
condition at the crucial hour 
the prosecution called an expert witness to calculate 
backwards and figure from hazelwoods 061 blood alcohol reading 
at 1030 am what the level might have been the midnight before 
the expert said hazelwood would have been drunk with a reading of 
perhaps 14 
but defense experts said the calculation method was nonsense 
and involved too many variables including whether hazelwood had 
something to drink aboard ship after the grounding 
hazelwood who did not testify in his own defense never 
explained neither did he say why he left the bridge in control of 
a third mate and went below during the transit in icy conditions 
the third mate gregory cousins tesified that hazelwood 
discussed with him a navigational plan to leave the shipping lanes 
maneuver around ice floes and return to the shipping lanes 
he asked if i felt comfortable with what we were going to do 
and i said yes recalled cousins he said do you feel 
comfortable enough that i can go below and get rid of some 
paperwork i said i felt very comfortable 
cousins did not hold the special coast guard pilotage 
endorsement for prince william sound a technicality which has been 
magnified during the trial 
hazelwood was the only officer with the special license the 
defense suggested that the coast guard may have waived the pilotage 
requirement that too remained unsettled 
cousins competence became less of an issue than the abilities 
of the helmsman robert kagan who was blamed by many for the 
disaster 
cousins indicated that kagan who had past problems with 
steering failed to follow his command for a 10degree right turn 
which would have taken the ship out of harms way 
did hazelwood know of kagans deficiencies did he err in 
leaving the bridge with this seaman at the helm 
the jury must answer those questions and decide whether 
hazelwoods actions constitute recklessness according to a legal 
definition as actions that are a gross deviation from the 
standard of conduct that a reasonable person would observe in the 
situation 
monday is set aside for legal discussions on how the judge 
should instruct the jury final arguments are scheduled for 
tuesday and superior court judge karl johnstone has said he hopes 
to instruct jurors in the law and submit the case to them the same 
day 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

