<TEXT>
polls opened in east germanys first free 
election sunday with the speed and manner of expected german 
unification a prime issue opposition parties alleged exsecret 
police may vote more than once to prop up communist candidates 
about 122 million voters were eligible to cast ballots for a 
400seat parliament with the likelihood of a merger with west 
germany sundays balloting could be the 41yearold nations first 
and last free election 
the vote marks the full transition to democracy from the once 
ironfisted communist rule and help set the pace of unification 
with west germany 
all major parties support unification but at a different pace 
some conservative parties urge a quick merger while leftist groups 
favor a more cautious approach most east germans agree such a 
joining is inevitable 
voters will choose from a dizzying array of 24 parties and 
groups the nations 22000 polling stations were to stay open from 
7 am 1 am est to 6 pm sunday west german television is 
expected to give computerized projections sunday night but 
official results are not expected until monday 
an east german television official said his crews for the first 
time had to make elaborate arrangements for an election 
this time we dont know what the result is going to be 
everything is new for us and we should expect some chaos said 
the official who refused to give his name 
many voters have been bewildered by the slates of candidates 
ranging from radical leftists and communists to archconservatives 
the campaigning was bitter and there is continuing fear about the 
oncedreaded secret police 
seven east german political parties claimed saturday that former 
secret police agents planned to use sets of false identity cards 
each with a different name to vote several times 
there is the suspicion of well prepared voterigging planned 
for march 18 the parties said in a statement 
the communistled government claims the secret police force has 
been virtually disbanded but many east germans have doubts 
the secret police force which officials say once numbered 
nearly 200000 agents and informers was the hardline communists 
main instrument of controlling east germans a popular revolution 
forced the ouster of hardline communist leader erich honecker on 
oct 18 and opened the way for the elections 
most former secret police agents reportedly remain loyal to the 
communists who were not expected to receive more than 18 percent 
of the vote 
in the city of erfurt the social democrats christian democrats 
and five other parties demanded the use of fingerprints to prevent 
secret police agents from casting extra ballots 
the parties also said they were making their concerns known to 
the un human rights commission in geneva 
an election commission representing all political parties has 
said voterigging is impossible 
the election will be monitored by observers from the 34 members 
of the conference on security and cooperation in europe which was 
founded to monitor compliance with the human rights provisions of 
the 1975 helsinki accords 
an american observer team will consist of staff members at the 
us embassy and six members of congress state department 
spokeswoman margaret tutwiler said 
the secret police known as the stasi in german already have 
played a part in the election 
the top candidate of a conservative east german party resigned 
last week after admitting he had worked with the secret police for 
years 
and martin kirchner the general secretary of another 
conservative party the east german christian democrats admitted 
having contacts with the secret police during several sporadic 
visits during the early 1980s he denied cooperating with them 
most campaigning ended friday but a few political parties made 
final pitches saturday 
the east german election is seen by many as a dress rehearsal 
for west german elections in december west german politicians have 
worked hard to build up an east german base for the time when 
unification comes 
in bonn president richard von weizsaecker said the elections 
would clear a healthy path to the unity of the germans 
the voters in the gdr east germans arent just deciding 
their own fate but also the stability of the european home in 
which we all want to live with equal rights and without fear of 
each other weizsaecker added 
many east berliners complained about what they considered west 
german arrogance and interference in their elections east german 
flags with the communist hammerandsickel insignia flew defiantly 
from several buildings 
its sad that we are so dependent on the west we feel like 
beggars as if we are asking for alms said marlies clausenitzer 
a 50yearold arts teacher from the town of schoenhausen just 
outside east berlin 
the election will be followed by efforts to form a new 
government to replace the communistled coalition now ruling east 
germany the large number of parties could make it difficult for 
one party to win a majority creating the need for another 
coalition 
also on election eve a west berlin newspaper reported that east 
germanys caretaker government has demanded an immediate financial 
bailout from bonn to prevent economic collapse 
east germany urgently needs 5 billion marks 294 billion to 
provide for the population and prevent economic collapse the 
berliner morgenpost newspaper said 
according to the report west german chancellor helmut kohl has 
refused to act on the east german request pending the outcome of 
sundays elections kohl has said he is not willing to pour good 
money into a bad system 
