<TEXT>
teenagers on drugs are at least three times 
more likely to attempt suicide than drugfree adolescents 
according to a study of patients at drug treatment centers 
dr richard h schwartz a vienna va pediatrician who 
coauthored a report published in the american journal of diseases 
of children said the research shows that drugs play a powerful 
role in the large numbers of teenage suicides 
theres no question that the drugs themselves can lead to 
depressive effects that lead to suicide attempts he said 
the more easily obtainable is the drug the greater the adverse 
effects suicide attempts increase dramatically 
suicide is the third leading cause of death among 15 to 
24yearold americans in virginia schwartz said it is the second 
leading cause of death among this age group 
schwartz said his study involved testing and questioning 298 
adolescent patients at four treatment centers he identified only as 
being in three separate areas east of the mississippi river 
twothirds of those surveyed admitted they had thoughts about 
committing suicide and 30 percent said they had made actual suicide 
attempts 
earlier studies said schwartz show that between 6 and 7 
percent of the general population attempt suicide in adolescence 
schwartz said the patients in his study were between 13 and 19 
years old most 93 percent were white and 66 percent were male 
the most popular drug among the group was marijuana with 
alcohol a distant second other drugs such as crack cocaine 
angel dust and lsd also were used 
among those who attempted suicide 40 percent said they made the 
attempt within eight hours after using drugs 
although there probably are multiple factors that lead to 
suicide attempts schwartz said the higher rate among drug users 
may be attributed to the depressive effects or low that 
develops after using some drugs 
some drugs in and of themselves have depressive effects 
alcohol does and so does pcp or angel dust and lsd said 
schwartz for drugs that are stimulants such as crack or cocaine 
the depression is a rebound they go up very high and the higher 
the high the lower the low 
following a crack binge for instance he said there will be an 
almost intolerable depression and many drug users see no way 
out but suicide 
most of the suicide attempts were of low lethality said 
schwartz with 61 percent requiring no medical attention but 10 
percent tried to kill themselves at the wheel of a car and 8 
percent tried to hang themselves 
about 15 percent of those attempting suicide spent time in 
intensive care said schwartz these were not superficial wrist 
slashings but serious attempts that could have resulted in death 
without prompt medical care 
the physician said he and his coauthor american university 
psychologist alan l berman were astounded that almost half of 
the teens who seriously attempted suicide reported that lethal 
means for doing it again were still in their family homes 
schwartz said 23 percent of those who tried to kill themselves 
said their families continued to keep firearms and ammunition 
around the home afterwards 
you cannot keep weapons at home like that if there is an 
adolescent on drugs he said you can assume a oneinnine 
chance of multiple suicide attempts so you need to get rid of 
firearms among successful suicides theres a growing tendency to 
use firearms 
the study by schwartz and berman is in the march issue of the 
american journal of diseases of children 
