senate leaders struggling to keep a 
compromise clean air agreement from unraveling hope this week to 
fend off a series of strengthening amendments that the white 
house calls too expensive 
returning from a weeklong recess senators renew debate tuesday 
on the farreaching air pollution control legislation that has 
preoccupied the senate most of this month 
among the thorniest issues are whether to go along with a plea 
from sen robert byrd dwva for assistance to any coal miners 
who lose their jobs because of new pollution curbs and over 
attempts by more than a dozen senators to toughen controls on 
smogcausing pollutants from automobiles 
meanwhile similar legislation in the house has begun to move 
the house energy and commerce committee begins this week to 
consider details of the bill 
although president bush has indicated he would like to have a 
clean air bill in time for his signature by earth day which will 
be celebrated april 22 no one on capitol hill predicts a bill will 
be ready by then 
the clean air legislation somewhat different versions in the 
senate and house represent the first major changes in 13 years in 
the 1970 clean air act bush as well as most members of congress 
acknowledge tougher controls on air pollution are overdue 
but getting a bill through congress has pitted regional groups 
against one another and prompted intense lobbying by a variety of 
industries who argue that the controls under consideration are too 
expensive and threaten the nations economy 
the house and senate bills impose significantly tougher controls 
on smogcausing pollutants from both automobiles and industrial 
sources require industry to install new equipment to curb toxic 
chemical releases that now total more than 27 billion pounds a 
year and for the first time require sharp reductions in sulfur 
dioxide and nitrogen oxide emissions from coalfired electric power 
plants to curb acid rain 
but a coalition of senators argue that a compromise agreement 
with the white house after weeks of closeddoor negotiations 
substantially weakened the senate bill especially its curbs to 
control urban smog by tightening emissions from automobiles 
sens timothy wirth dcolo and pete wilson rcalif planned 
to push an amendment early in the week that would restore a tougher 
second round of tailpipe controls and require automakers to produce 
a specific number of alternative fuel vehicles 
the tougher controls in the wirthwilson amendment have been 
strongly criticized by the bush administration and characterized as 
likely deal breakers that could scuttle the compromise 
agreement and threaten passage of clean air legislation altogether 
byrds coal miner assistance amendment also has been called a 
threat to the senatewhite house agreement and will have to be 
dealt with before serious progress can be made on other provisions 
according to senate aides 
senate majority leader george mitchell dmaine had been 
prepared to vote on the byrd proposal before the senate adjourned 
for its recess but mitchell postponed a vote after it became 
unclear whether he had enough votes to rebuff byrd who wields 
considerable power among senators because of his chairmanship of 
the appropriations committee 
the byrd plan calls for the government to pay miners between 50 
percent to 80 percent of their most recent salaries for four years 
after they become unemployed if their job loss stems from tougher 
acid rain pollution controls on coal utilities 
the controversy over the coal miner provisions threatened to 
complicate attempts by mitchell and sen bob dole rkan the 
minority leader to keep support for the compromise legislation 
intact 
if the assistance program is approved it could cause the white 
house to withdraw support for the legislative package and cause 
other senators to seek similar job protection provisions for other 
workers such as the petrochemical or steel industries who also 
face possible harm 
but if byrd is rebuffed he could persuade enough senators to 
oppose the bill to prevent its passage 
in the house meanwhile rep john dingell dmich chairman of 
the energy and commerce committee said he wanted to complete 
action on clean air legislation before the easter recess april 6 
dingell last week cautioned committee members to proceed 
without undue delay and procrastination but said he anticipated 
long and difficult committee sessions with the consideration 
of amendments scheduled to begin tuesday 
among the yetunresolved problems facing the house committee is 
whether to provide assistance to coalburning utilities in the ohio 
valley and elsewhere in the midwest that meet tougher acid rain 
controls 
the bush administration staunchly opposes a national fee or tax 
to help the dirtiest electric plants cut pollution but rep philip 
sharp dind is planning to seek such a fee on industrial 
emitters of sulfur dioxide 
rep henry waxman dcalif and other members also are expected 
to seek tougher emission controls on toxic and smogcausing 
pollutants from industrial sources and further reductions in 
automobile emissions both through tighter tailpipe controls and 
wider use of alternative fuel vehicles 
