average fuel economy for automobiles has 
declined each of the last two years reversing an earlier fiveyear 
trend toward more efficient automobiles an environmental group 
said sunday 
the environmental action foundation cited statistics from the 
environmental protection agency and national highway traffic safety 
administration 
according to the government figures cited by the group the 
average fuel economy of 1990 model cars is expected to be 282 
miles per gallon compared with 283 mpg for 1989 model cars and 
287 mpg for 1988 model cars 
an analysis by the epa attributed the trend to the manufacture 
of heavier cars with quicker acceleration times and the use of 
larger engines with greater horsepower 
in terms of fuel efficiency were heading south on a 
northbound oneway street said robert dewey of the 
environmental action foundation 
the figures showed that between the 1983 and 1988 model years 
the fuel efficiency of both domestic and imported cars increased 
steadily from 264 mpg to 287 mpg 
dewey said the government figures also show that the gap between 
imports and domestic cars is narrowing in terms of fuel efficiency 
in 1986 imports on a fleetwide basis were 8 mpg more efficient 
than domestic cars in the 1990 models the difference has narrowed 
to 3 mpg he said 
these figures clearly dispel the myth that japanese automakers 
still hold a huge efficiency advantage over domestics said dewey 
the advantage of japanese automakers in past years over domestic 
fleets in fuel efficiency largely has been based on the fact the 
japanese built smaller cars in recent years with government 
restrictions on the number of imports the japanese imports have 
consisted of more large less fuel efficient vehicles 
there has been increasing concern among environmentalists over 
the fuel efficiency of cars because the more gasoline cars use the 
more they emit carbon dioxide which is linked to global warming 
legislation expected to be considered later this year in the 
senate would require automakers to achieve a fleetwide 40 mpg by 
the end of the decade efforts also are expected to put a similar 
provision into the clean air legislation that now is before house 
energy and commerce committee the automakers have vigorously 
lobbied against such legislation 
