than other countries examined 
infant mortality rates ranged from a low of 5 deaths per 1000 
live births in japan to 25 deaths per 1000 in the soviet union 
the us rate was 10 deaths per 1000 live births equal to or 
worse than nine countries 
the united states had a murder rate for male youths four to 
five times that of other developed countries but mexico had a rate 
twice that of the united states 
the united states compared favorably in rates of youth 
unemployment and suicide 
miller said statistics on infant mortality show the united 
states does a good job of saving ill babies that would have died in 
less developed countries but low average birth weights suggest the 
united states does a poor job of prenatal care he said 
its lack of will miller said were not willing to spend 
those preventative dollars its criminal really 
he said the comparisons suggest the united states will not meet 
goals set by president bush to make the united states rank first in 
science and math education by the end of the 1990s 
the report compared 12 industrialized countries australia 
canada france germany great britain hungary italy japan 
norway soviet union sweden united states it also provided some 
information on four countries listed as developing israel mexico 
india and china 
the study used various types of data from the countries and 
comparisons often were based on figures from different years 
in a minority report republicans on the committee said such 
variations limit its value they said the report cannot be used 
as evidence to prove that a new child policy agenda is needed 
republicans said the most significant comparison showed the 
united states has the highest proportion of singleparent families 
while 229 percent of family households in the united states 
are headed by a singleparent less than 6 percent of households in 
japan are headed by a single parent they said 
this factor has widespread implications for many indicators 
including poverty infant mortality rates teenage pregnancy rates 
abortions outofwedlock births and even educational 
achievement the republicans said 
</TEXT>
