<TEXT>
a dream vaclav havel cherished 
through years of persecution came true sunday the brave 2000 
people of charter 77 eastern europes oldest human rights 
movement met for the first time 
they were packed into the elegant prague building where havel 
last november negotiated the overthrow of stalinism with communist 
leaders aged men bent old women bearded hippies and freshfaced 
youth relished their freedom to be together at last 
the feeling is excellent beamed petr pospichal a longtime 
dissident who works for civic forum the movement born out of 
charter that overturned communist rule last fall after all these 
years we just now realize how many we are 
for many years prisonerturnedpresident havel said in 
brief opening remarks i had a dream i had this dream when i was 
free but more often when i was in prison 
it was a dream that all signatories of charter 77 would meet 
one day in some prague hall and will talk without being disturbed 
by the police this dream this archetypal vision is being 
fulfilled today 
but the joy for havel and many others was tinged with grief 
for those who did not live to see the triumph of the 13year 
struggle waged by eastern europes oldest and arguably most 
diverse movement for freedom and human dignity 
among those mourned was jan patocka a philosopher who like 
havel was one of the first signatories of charter 77 he was one of 
its first spokesmen and spiritual father of its vision of founding 
a civic society in which free citizens take responsibility for 
their actions 
patocka died in march 1977 two months after charter was born 
after intensive police interrogation 
charter whose ideals are now expressed in state policy rather 
than underground literature circulated among friends was unique in 
eastern europe in uniting many different strands of thought 
it began as an association of 240 intellectuals who signed a new 
year manifesto protesting the suppression of freedom in 
czechoslovakia and grew to become one of the most vigorous 
supporters of human rights in eastern europe 
in charter religious activists worked with excommunists 
expelled from the party in the purges that followed the crushing of 
reform in 1968 wildly unconventional rock musicians met staid 
intellectuals young peace campaigners aligned with aging 
preworld war ii democrats 
maintaining that unity will be the tough task facing chartists 
in civic forum after free elections june 8 in which it is expected 
to garner the largest share of the vote 
these are very different worries from those of the past 13 years 
battling the repression of communist rulers who feared such broad 
and potentially dangerous dissent 
men like havel and jiri dienstbier now foreign minister in the 
postrevolutionary government were constantly detained 
interrogated watched and jailed 
the harassment brought them international renown as defenders of 
human rights and democracy in czechoslovakia and eastern europe as 
a whole 
but charter was also signed by hundreds of lesserknown 
individuals who braved persecution to subscribe to the founding 
documents ideals exercising what havel in a famous 1975 essay 
dubbed the power of the powerless 
stanislav stransky an upright 68yearold was one of those 
first jailed in 1948 by the communists and forced all his life to 
work only at menial manual labor he helped charter by maintaining 
an illegal printing press 
for him sunday was a great day because i met all these 
people i only ever heard about 
during the communists rule chartists considered a gathering of 
even 30 of their number a success over the secret police 
on sunday about 2000 people came from all over the country to 
chat listen to speeches and buy the onceunderground publications 
that as recently as last october earned their editors months in 
jail 
mulling the future however jan urban a prominent former 
dissident who now heads civic forum found trepidation clouding his 
joy 
on the one hand its beautiful to see all these people 
together and to feel that something has happened urban said 
on the other hand its frightening to see what may happen 
very soon in this country to see that after so many years of no 
politics people arent prepared for the problems they will face 
under a stalinist system which politicized everything except 
politics itself charter tried to initiate debate and a broad range 
of political thought 
its members typed out by hand hundreds of documents discussing 
issues from the environment to ethnic tensions the economy to 
womens rights 
it was this activity that enabled civic forum to assume control 
within just three weeks when the communist hold on power crumbled 
last november 
discussing all those things for such a long time it made us 
ready to serve urban said at a moment of crisis people were 
able to go not to a stokers place dienstbiers former job but 
to the ministry of foreign affairs 
