<TEXT>
al hirschfelds caricatures of theater 
personalities have graced the pages of the new york times for six 
decades but the master of line drawing is not done learning 
all i know is that when it works im aware of it but how 
its accomplished i dont know said hirschfeld who turns 87 in 
june 
now 98 of his works 31 of them originals are featured in a 
traveling exhibit that premiered saturday at the brandywine river 
museum the first of 15 stops on a us tour organized by the trust 
for museum exhibitions 
the mainly blackandwhite exhibit gives viewers plenty of 
chances to search his subjects for the hidden name of his daughter 
nina a hirschfeld trademark 
hirschfeld said the exhibit puts his early sins prominently on 
display but his illustrations from the 1920s through the 1980s 
also show his development as an artist 
through trial and error you eliminate and eliminate and get 
down to the pure line and how it communicates to the viewer 
hirschfeld said friday the last drawing you do is the best one 
it should be 
hirschfeld spends his days finding the right lines to make the 
face be it sidney poitier or oliver hardy his seemingly simple 
sweeping stroke catches mikhail baryshnikov in air fred astaire 
dancing up a wall or leonard bernstein conducting an orchestra 
using basically an s on its side and a couple more sweeping 
strokes he creates the folded arms of peter ustinov in an 
imaginary odd couple role as oscar madison part of an 
unlikely casting series done for playbill 
his lines can be heavy to create the eyes nose and mouth of 
zero mostel as tevye in fiddler on the roof or hundreds maybe 
thousands of sharp wisps to capture his black bushy beard 
margo feiden whose new york galleries house several of the 
works in the exhibit said hirschfeld is doing his best work now 
its very clearly defined now said ms feiden who is 
hirschfelds agent its very distilled one day hes going 
to be able to draw a dot in the middle of the page and were going 
to be able to know who that is 
hiding the name of his daughter in his work began in 
philadelphia nina was born in 1945 while he was making a sketch 
for the philadelphia opening of the play are you with it so he 
put her name in the background he kept hiding ninas name for a 
while and when he tried to stop public demand wouldnt let him 
he cant get a handle on the fascination which once led to a 
60000 pentagon grant to a university of pennsylvania professor to 
study the search for ninas he thought it was insane and was 
even less impressed when the professor told him the work would help 
pilots read maps 
you drop a pebble in the water and the ripples never cease 
he said 
