<TEXT>
a tehran daily sunday criticized the 
governments campaign to curb irans population explosion an 
effort that has underlined ideological disputes between president 
hashemi rafsanjani and his radical rivals 
irans official islamic republic news agency monitored in 
nicosia quoted an editorial in the radical jomhuri islami 
newspaper as saying the government had taken an unprincipled 
approach in seeking to slow down population growth 
irans population is swelling at a rate of about 39 percent a 
year one of the highest in the world 
rafsanjani leader of irans socalled pragmatists has 
recognized that unchecked population growth threatens to outstrip 
economic development and jeopardize the countrys reconstruction 
drive following the august 1988 ceasefire in the war against iraq 
the government put the population at 55 million recently before 
the 1979 islamic revolution the figure was 37 million it is 
expected to top 100 million by the year 2010 
the jomhuri islami editorial reflected opposition by 
revolutionary hardliners to the birth control campaign the 
government began last year and the radicals growing criticism of 
rafsanjanis policies 
they argue that a large population will help iran become the 
leader of the islamic world and ensure its power and prosperity 
blunting population growth is central to rafsanjanis drive to 
revitalize irans limping economy expand industry and attract 
foreign investment which the antiwestern radicals charge 
undermines the purity of the revolution 
jomhuri islami noted those advocating population control warn 
that the current rate of increase is too high and that the 
country will not be able to provide food education medicines and 
so on 
it said they argue that the present shortcomings in social 
services are the natural outcome of rapid population growth 
even proper planning will not solve the problem and it is unlikely 
to establish harmony between the existing facilities and the 
populations needs 
on the other hand the editorial said opponents of population 
control argue that the main problem is migration of villagers 
to the cities and its side effects such as congestion in the 
capital and major cities 
tehran is bursting with a population that has doubled in recent 
years to about 7 million 
if tehran is exploding due to the high rate of population 
increase there are many abandoned villages throughout the country 
that are in miserable condition due to the lack of population 
the editorial said 
irans spiritual leader ayatollah ali khamenei has supported 
the governments campaign by declaring that birth control does not 
violate islam 
islam itself has been seen as a factor for the alarming surge in 
irans population since the revolution whose leaders stressed 
early marriage and encouraged large families 
the marriage rate doubled from 45 per thousand in 1975 to 98 
percent in 1983 according to available statistics 
but the economy has not been able to keep up 
there is a shortage of housing and schools and unemployment has 
risen tehran and other cities regularly suffer power cuts and 
water shortages food accounts for an estimated onethird of all 
imports because the agricultural sector has deteriorated alarmingly 
since 1979 
</TEXT>
