japans first lunar probe launched a smaller 
satellite into orbit around the moon early monday a government 
space official said 
the probe called the musesa satellite is circling the earth 
in a highly elliptical orbit that brought it within 10213 miles of 
the moon said yasunori matogawa spokesman for the 
governmentfunded institute of space and astronautical science 
shortly before the 400pound probe crossed the moons path 
during its swingby it released a second smaller satellite that 
was driven into lunar orbit by a kick motor he said 
matogawa said the procedure went as planned the smaller 
satellite will move in an orbit ranging from 12400 to 43400 miles 
from the moon 
the mission will give japan valuable experience in targeting 
orbits and in the use of swingbys for future spacecraft traveling 
to distant planets the musesa will pass the moon eight or nine 
more times during the next year it is expected to remain in orbit 
as the musesa crossed the moons path observation equipment 
aboard the probe photographed the moon but the images were not 
very clear because of the satellites relatively long distance from 
the moon matogawa said there is no observation equipment on the 
smaller satellite 
both the institute of space and astronautical science which is 
conducting the mission and japans other space agency the 
national space development agency have plans for manned space 
flights and interplanetary travel 
the satellite launched in january from uchinoura space center 
in southern japan is a symbolic step forward in japans budding 
space program until now only the united states and the soviet 
union have sent missions to the moon 
