a group of exxon corp shareholders claiming 
the oil companys environmental problems have threatened the value 
of their holdings are demanding a meeting with the companys 
chairman to explain exxons recent accidents and plans for avoiding 
them in the future 
in a letter dated friday managers of pension funds from 
california new york and massachusetts which own more than 14 
million shares of exxon stock called on exxon chairman lawrence g 
rawl to discuss the string of accidents that have wreaked 
environmental havoc from alaska to new york 
the group said it wants the nations largest oil company to 
disclose its plans for implementing environmental safety systems 
and improving its environmental record 
we want to emphasize the importance of holding this meeting as 
soon as possible said the letter signed by gray davis 
california state comptroller and manager of the nations largest 
public pension fund elizabeth holtzman new york city comptroller 
